So today, we're going to talk about MAIVS, or multiplex

4
00:00:12.880 --> 00:00:16.580
assays of variant effects, as they apply to cancer predisposition

5
00:00:16.640 --> 00:00:20.540
genes. And at least the examples I'll give will

6
00:00:20.580 --> 00:00:24.100
be from the breast cancer, ovarian cancer predisposition genes, and

7
00:00:24.140 --> 00:00:27.750
then Jacob Kitzman, who's joining me here today,

8
00:00:27.780 --> 00:00:31.360
will talk more about the colorectal and some other angles.

9
00:00:35.300 --> 00:00:37.100
So here are the two presentations.

10
00:00:37.140 --> 00:00:40.020
Originally, we were going to have Leah Starita from the University of Washington

11
00:00:40.120 --> 00:00:44.020
join us, but she had to pull out. So we'll just spend a little bit more time on

12
00:00:44.060 --> 00:00:45.540
our two talks, 30 minutes each,

13
00:00:46.500 --> 00:00:50.480
as we walk through the principles of MAIVS and then some

14
00:00:50.520 --> 00:00:53.020
of the discoveries that have been made in recent times.

15
00:00:54.640 --> 00:00:55.180
Okay.

16
00:01:04.401 --> 00:01:06.800
Okay, so I'll start with my presentation.

17
00:01:07.440 --> 00:01:11.270
I'm going to be talking about some of the work that we've done on BRCA2,

18
00:01:12.060 --> 00:01:14.000
the breast and ovarian cancer predisposition gene,

19
00:01:16.020 --> 00:01:18.260
and then talk about how we might combine MAIVS together.

20
00:01:18.380 --> 00:01:21.460
So as more and more of these types of studies are starting to get published and

21
00:01:21.520 --> 00:01:22.240
data coming out,

22
00:01:23.060 --> 00:01:26.940
we're finding multiple different experiments done on the same gene.

23
00:01:28.640 --> 00:01:31.460
The hypothesis is that there's benefit to putting these things together.

24
00:01:31.520 --> 00:01:32.740
They may actually improve the

25
00:01:33.820 --> 00:01:35.540
accuracy of some of our measures.

26
00:01:37.500 --> 00:01:39.240
So I want to talk a little bit about

27
00:01:40.060 --> 00:01:43.560
that work and ways that you might approach putting the data sets together.

28
00:01:47.300 --> 00:01:49.340
Okay. So here are my financial disclosures.

29
00:01:50.520 --> 00:01:53.200
Okay, so let me just introduce you to some breast cancer genes.

30
00:01:54.160 --> 00:01:57.500
What we're looking at on the x-axis is just the frequency in the population.

31
00:01:57.880 --> 00:02:01.540
So most of these are fairly rare. BRCA1 and BRCA2

32
00:02:01.580 --> 00:02:05.430
mutations are probably found in the population at about one in 300.

33
00:02:07.900 --> 00:02:09.880
And then the effect size, how high is the risk?

34
00:02:10.420 --> 00:02:14.340
So you can see BRCA1 and 2 up here as high-risk genes, as I said, are

35
00:02:14.480 --> 00:02:18.000
reasonably rare, but there's a lot of other low-risk or moderate-risk

36
00:02:18.060 --> 00:02:18.480
genes

37
00:02:19.780 --> 00:02:21.660
that are listed on the diagram here.

38
00:02:21.720 --> 00:02:23.320
So there's plenty of genes for us to play with.

39
00:02:24.320 --> 00:02:27.760
In the breast cancer field, we think of maybe 10 or 12 genes that

40
00:02:28.540 --> 00:02:31.200
meet those criteria that are actually driving breast cancer.

41
00:02:31.840 --> 00:02:34.520
So if we wanted to do MAIVS on all of these, that's a fair amount of work.

42
00:02:35.020 --> 00:02:37.700
But as you'll see as I go through the presentation, quite a few of these have

43
00:02:37.760 --> 00:02:39.060
already been attempted.

44
00:02:42.760 --> 00:02:46.660
So as we do a lot of clinical genetic testing on all these

45
00:02:46.700 --> 00:02:50.180
various genes, we find a lot of variants of uncertain significance, and this is

46
00:02:50.220 --> 00:02:53.750
probably a term that many of you will have come across already.

47
00:02:54.280 --> 00:02:58.080
So essentially when we do genetic testing, the idea is can we find a known

48
00:02:58.120 --> 00:03:01.760
pathogenic variant that will inform the care of the patient?

49
00:03:03.340 --> 00:03:07.260
But many times we actually find these variants of uncertain significance, and these

50
00:03:07.320 --> 00:03:10.640
tend to be missenses around intronic or in-frame deletions or

51
00:03:10.680 --> 00:03:13.000
insertions. We don't know what they do.

52
00:03:14.920 --> 00:03:18.359
And as a result, the patients do not benefit from the clinical

53
00:03:19.780 --> 00:03:23.520
modification, the clinical management strategies that we can apply when we

54
00:03:23.540 --> 00:03:26.480
know that there's a pathogenic variant in the particular gene.

55
00:03:28.340 --> 00:03:32.120
And so these are listed out here. And in breast cancer, we often think of

56
00:03:32.180 --> 00:03:36.020
things like enhanced screening with MRIs and mammograms.

57
00:03:37.560 --> 00:03:39.220
And we can also do prophylactic surgery.

58
00:03:39.300 --> 00:03:42.940
So there are reasons why it's important to figure out what these VUS are

59
00:03:42.980 --> 00:03:46.780
doing. Currently, clinically, if you find a VUS, the

60
00:03:46.800 --> 00:03:50.450
genetic test is essentially thrown away, and you have to focus on

61
00:03:50.540 --> 00:03:53.460
managing the patient based on their personal and their family history of the

62
00:03:53.480 --> 00:03:54.460
disease. Okay?

63
00:03:55.520 --> 00:03:57.040
So there's thousands of these things out there.

64
00:03:57.200 --> 00:04:01.100
If you look at some of the bigger genes in breast cancer, BRCA1, BRCA2, PALB2,

65
00:04:01.160 --> 00:04:03.060
ATM, these are all quite large genes.

66
00:04:04.990 --> 00:04:08.920
There are thousands of VUS that are in the ClinVar database that

67
00:04:08.960 --> 00:04:12.920
remain unresolved. And so this is the purpose of MAIVS and the application of

68
00:04:12.960 --> 00:04:16.440
MAIVS to this set of genes is to figure out what all these things do.

69
00:04:16.481 --> 00:04:20.190
Can we convert them from unknown or uncertain over to either

70
00:04:20.200 --> 00:04:22.340
benign or pathogenic? That's the concept.

71
00:04:24.220 --> 00:04:27.580
And of course, MAIVS are ideal for this kind of thing because we can do large

72
00:04:27.620 --> 00:04:31.420
multiplexed assays, and this is just a general diagram where we

73
00:04:31.460 --> 00:04:35.100
can select a model system, a cell type that we want to use for a

74
00:04:35.200 --> 00:04:35.580
culture.

75
00:04:37.360 --> 00:04:41.040
We can make many, many different mutants and put them all in the cells together,

76
00:04:41.520 --> 00:04:42.680
hopefully one per cell.

77
00:04:44.460 --> 00:04:48.040
And then we essentially apply a selection process that could be

78
00:04:48.080 --> 00:04:50.840
viability, it could be a response to a challenge like a

79
00:04:51.820 --> 00:04:54.620
DNA-damaging agent or something like that.

80
00:04:54.710 --> 00:04:56.120
There's many different ways of doing that.

81
00:04:57.620 --> 00:05:00.560
Obviously, you have to know your disease, and you have to know your gene in order

82
00:05:00.620 --> 00:05:01.820
to select those processes.

83
00:05:02.820 --> 00:05:06.640
But once you've done that, this is where the MAIV technology comes in, is that

84
00:05:06.720 --> 00:05:10.320
we can just harvest DNA out of all of these cells all at the same time,

85
00:05:11.740 --> 00:05:14.550
amplify up the little regions of interest, and sequence them.

86
00:05:14.880 --> 00:05:17.220
Sequence them super deep, hundreds of millions of reads.

87
00:05:17.840 --> 00:05:21.300
And from that, you can do the number of counts of each variant

88
00:05:22.120 --> 00:05:24.670
in the final data set. Right? And so by

89
00:05:26.160 --> 00:05:29.800
comparing counts at early time points and late time points, there's other ways to

90
00:05:29.820 --> 00:05:33.420
do it, but if you just do it that way, you actually end up with a simple functional

91
00:05:33.520 --> 00:05:35.220
score. It's a ratio of, let's say,

92
00:05:36.160 --> 00:05:39.660
day one to day five, or day five to day 15, that sort of idea.

93
00:05:40.160 --> 00:05:43.380
You can actually ratio the data and get a functional score.

94
00:05:44.520 --> 00:05:46.760
So let me give you the example of BRCA2.

95
00:05:46.800 --> 00:05:50.360
I'll just walk through some of the data that we published last year on this topic.

96
00:05:50.960 --> 00:05:54.680
So BRCA2 is a well-known predisposition gene for breast and ovarian cancer.

97
00:05:56.100 --> 00:05:59.840
It's involved in homologous recombination DNA repair, so generally

98
00:05:59.880 --> 00:06:03.824
double-strand breaks or replication fork issues.We know

99
00:06:03.834 --> 00:06:07.824
that if you have a protein-truncating mutation in BRCA2, which is what we

100
00:06:07.864 --> 00:06:11.844
call a pathogenic variant, we're at about a 69% lifetime risk of breast

101
00:06:11.924 --> 00:06:15.004
cancer and about a 15% lifetime risk of ovarian.

102
00:06:15.064 --> 00:06:18.084
And there's a few other cancers that come along for the ride as well, as shown

103
00:06:18.144 --> 00:06:21.784
here. Here's the gene down below or the

104
00:06:21.824 --> 00:06:25.484
protein, and we focus here, the red box is on the DNA binding domain.

105
00:06:25.504 --> 00:06:29.474
And the MAVS that have been done so far on BRCA2 have all

106
00:06:29.504 --> 00:06:32.284
really focused on this region. You might say, "Well, why?

107
00:06:32.384 --> 00:06:35.863
Why only that piece?" Well, it's because all the known

108
00:06:35.904 --> 00:06:39.504
pathogenic missense variants, single amino acid changes that are known

109
00:06:39.864 --> 00:06:41.924
clinically, are all in this region.

110
00:06:42.584 --> 00:06:44.584
There essentially are no others that are known.

111
00:06:44.693 --> 00:06:48.364
There are a few sprinkled around that are splice variants that result in

112
00:06:48.384 --> 00:06:51.824
truncation of the protein. But if you're just talking about a true

113
00:06:51.904 --> 00:06:54.464
missense, they're all in this DNA binding domain.

114
00:06:54.724 --> 00:06:58.564
So these large functional screens have focused in on that region as a

115
00:06:58.604 --> 00:06:58.984
result.

116
00:07:01.544 --> 00:07:04.034
So here's the schematic of the actual experiment.

117
00:07:04.144 --> 00:07:06.564
First thing I'll tell you is that we're using HAP1 cells.

118
00:07:07.204 --> 00:07:08.064
These are haploid,

119
00:07:09.284 --> 00:07:11.464
so that means they've got one copy of each chromosome.

120
00:07:11.944 --> 00:07:15.344
That's ideal for a MAVE targeting type experiment where you're trying to knock in

121
00:07:15.424 --> 00:07:19.344
all these mutations. Now you only have to target the cell one time.

122
00:07:19.724 --> 00:07:21.284
You only have to get it into one chromosome.

123
00:07:21.604 --> 00:07:23.744
If that was a diploid cell, you have to get it into both.

124
00:07:24.224 --> 00:07:27.204
So it's so much easier with a haploid line.

125
00:07:27.244 --> 00:07:30.834
The caveat to that is that you don't always know that this haploid cell is

126
00:07:30.844 --> 00:07:33.624
behaving the right way. Is it behaving the same as a diploid cell?

127
00:07:34.504 --> 00:07:37.244
But it's a starting point, and so many of the experiments that have been

128
00:07:37.344 --> 00:07:41.304
done for at least cancer genes have focused on the

129
00:07:41.324 --> 00:07:45.264
HAP1 cells. And the original use of that was the Nature 2018

130
00:07:45.364 --> 00:07:49.304
paper from Findlay, where they studied BRCA1 and reported that out, and then we

131
00:07:49.324 --> 00:07:51.344
did the same thing for BRCA2 last year.

132
00:07:52.364 --> 00:07:54.044
Here's the DNA binding domain up above.

133
00:07:54.584 --> 00:07:56.384
You can see our little molecular scissors here.

134
00:07:57.024 --> 00:08:00.774
Each exon is done in its own experiment, so one exon at a time,

135
00:08:01.524 --> 00:08:03.004
and obviously in triplicate.

136
00:08:04.764 --> 00:08:07.524
And then we basically rely on viability.

137
00:08:07.684 --> 00:08:11.324
So if you take out a homologous recombination gene out of the HAP1 cells,

138
00:08:11.764 --> 00:08:14.444
they will start to die. It's a basic viability effect.

139
00:08:15.684 --> 00:08:19.254
And so what we do is we harvest cells at day five, where we've

140
00:08:19.304 --> 00:08:23.284
integrated all the mutations. We've put them into the endogenous

141
00:08:23.344 --> 00:08:25.584
locus, into the actual genome of the cells,

142
00:08:26.424 --> 00:08:30.104
and then we wait until day 14. And if it's a nasty mutation, they've been

143
00:08:30.204 --> 00:08:31.224
dying at day 14.

144
00:08:32.284 --> 00:08:34.664
If it's a wild-type variant, they've been growing.

145
00:08:34.754 --> 00:08:38.564
And so you can make these ratios when you sequence of day 5 to day 14.

146
00:08:38.744 --> 00:08:39.664
Is it going up or down?

147
00:08:40.544 --> 00:08:44.064
That results in a functional score, which can be plotted out as a diagram like

148
00:08:44.124 --> 00:08:44.344
this.

149
00:08:45.924 --> 00:08:47.264
So here's what the data looks like.

150
00:08:48.124 --> 00:08:50.644
Here's your functional score of that ratio that I was mentioning.

151
00:08:51.184 --> 00:08:54.624
And you see a nice separation of your nonsense variants and your synonymous

152
00:08:54.644 --> 00:08:55.104
variants.

153
00:08:55.964 --> 00:08:59.804
And of course, this is ideal for all MAVEs that you would do for any disease

154
00:08:59.884 --> 00:09:02.744
state or for any gene that you would want to study. You need standards.

155
00:09:02.984 --> 00:09:05.164
You need known pathogenics and known benigns.

156
00:09:05.853 --> 00:09:08.664
And that's where it becomes more difficult, I think, for some diseases where we

157
00:09:08.704 --> 00:09:12.544
don't have many of those controls. We don't really know what to use as controls.

158
00:09:13.164 --> 00:09:16.814
But in the context of BRCA2, where it's been studied a lot, there's lots and lots

159
00:09:16.864 --> 00:09:20.644
of these controls available. So there's a very nice separation between those two

160
00:09:20.744 --> 00:09:23.524
peaks. And then you see all the other types of variants.

161
00:09:24.704 --> 00:09:27.104
In green are the missenses. There's thousands of them in here,

162
00:09:27.964 --> 00:09:29.944
all evaluated in the same basic experiment.

163
00:09:30.024 --> 00:09:33.124
We've pooled all the data together and normalized across all the exons.

164
00:09:33.464 --> 00:09:36.144
So it's all one experiment, essentially.

165
00:09:39.404 --> 00:09:43.174
Now, how do you analyze the data? Okay, you've got this ratio, but how do you now

166
00:09:43.174 --> 00:09:47.004
align it all and come up with probability models

167
00:09:47.084 --> 00:09:49.474
or classification models based on that function?

168
00:09:50.044 --> 00:09:52.124
There's lots of different ways to do that.

169
00:09:52.134 --> 00:09:56.104
There are programs out there such as Enrich 2, which you can just put your data in

170
00:09:56.124 --> 00:09:59.304
there, and it does it on the basis of a simple precision model or a

171
00:09:59.344 --> 00:10:03.244
two-component mixture model. In other words, it's basically saying, I know where

172
00:10:03.264 --> 00:10:07.024
my two sets of standards are. I can model a two-component Gaussian

173
00:10:07.124 --> 00:10:10.404
curve on that and make a binary cut point to say,

174
00:10:11.324 --> 00:10:14.544
left of that is bad, right of that is good. That sort of idea.

175
00:10:14.604 --> 00:10:18.204
That's a simplistic model, but it is what people were originally doing.

176
00:10:18.744 --> 00:10:22.564
You can also go to 95% probability or precision models.

177
00:10:23.184 --> 00:10:27.064
So only the things that are in the top 5% on the benign or the

178
00:10:27.104 --> 00:10:31.024
pathogenic, or the non-functional and the functional sites would be picked as the

179
00:10:31.064 --> 00:10:34.584
nasty ones. Everything that fell in between that still sits there as

180
00:10:34.664 --> 00:10:35.194
VUS.

181
00:10:36.144 --> 00:10:39.524
And then there's also the idea of a continuous probability

182
00:10:39.564 --> 00:10:43.404
model all the way from one to 100. And so every variant gets its

183
00:10:43.464 --> 00:10:47.364
own probability, its own score, and then you have to figure out how do

184
00:10:47.404 --> 00:10:49.824
you make thresholds or cut points in that experiment.

185
00:10:51.004 --> 00:10:54.044
We actually went beyond that, and we actually used what's called VarCall.

186
00:10:54.644 --> 00:10:58.124
So this is a model that was developed by Ed Iverson at Duke University

187
00:10:59.524 --> 00:11:03.244
a number of years ago, and it's essentially a two-component Gaussian model based on

188
00:11:03.284 --> 00:11:05.884
two sets of standards, but it allows for

189
00:11:09.144 --> 00:11:11.964
probabilities based on replicates and batch effects.

190
00:11:12.164 --> 00:11:14.843
It accommodates all of that.

191
00:11:15.744 --> 00:11:17.794
So you actually give it a prior probability.

192
00:11:18.844 --> 00:11:22.804
So we use alpha missense. If you apply alpha missense to all these missenses, alpha

193
00:11:22.844 --> 00:11:26.564
missense predicted that 20% would be deleterious or

194
00:11:26.574 --> 00:11:29.144
non-functional. So we give it a prior of 0.2.

195
00:11:30.424 --> 00:11:34.264
And then we roll all the functional data in on top to give a posterior

196
00:11:34.304 --> 00:11:35.624
probability.

197
00:11:37.644 --> 00:11:41.164
One of the advantages of VarCall is it rolls the data out into seven different

198
00:11:41.204 --> 00:11:45.124
variant categories. So these are pathogenic strong, pathogenic

199
00:11:45.224 --> 00:11:49.184
moderate, pathogenic supporting, VUS, and then the same

200
00:11:49.224 --> 00:11:51.064
three categories for the strongs.

201
00:11:52.104 --> 00:11:55.664
Now, some of these categories might be reminiscent to you in that

202
00:11:56.184 --> 00:11:59.484
they are actually the seven categories that we use in the

203
00:11:59.524 --> 00:12:03.204
ACMG, so the ClinGen ACMG classification

204
00:12:03.244 --> 00:12:05.804
models that are now widely used for disease genes.

205
00:12:05.844 --> 00:12:09.652
It's the same seven categories.So essentially what we've done with the

206
00:12:09.692 --> 00:12:13.472
functional data is we've calibrated it to the ACMG classification

207
00:12:13.552 --> 00:12:17.492
model so that the data can be directly added into that classification

208
00:12:17.532 --> 00:12:21.392
model. Some other functional assays, as I said, just have binary, so

209
00:12:21.452 --> 00:12:24.152
two regions, two groups, or three groups.

210
00:12:24.632 --> 00:12:27.852
How do you integrate that data into the ACMG models?

211
00:12:27.882 --> 00:12:31.602
That's a challenge, right? But with this, it's just easier because you already have

212
00:12:31.632 --> 00:12:33.232
the seven categories up front.

213
00:12:36.192 --> 00:12:39.951
Okay, so back to the data itself. Here's your seven categories with the color

214
00:12:40.052 --> 00:12:42.452
key. Here's the different types of variants.

215
00:12:42.632 --> 00:12:46.572
You can see that all the nonsenses are pathogenic strongs, high strong,

216
00:12:47.392 --> 00:12:50.732
high probability of being pathogenic, so that makes perfect sense.

217
00:12:51.012 --> 00:12:54.592
You're truncating the protein. All the synonymous, so single amino

218
00:12:54.672 --> 00:12:55.172
acid,

219
00:12:58.052 --> 00:13:00.232
nucleotide changes that don't change the amino acid.

220
00:13:00.792 --> 00:13:03.252
The vast majority of those are actually benign strong.

221
00:13:03.272 --> 00:13:06.472
That makes sense as well. And then about 13% to

222
00:13:06.492 --> 00:13:09.672
14% of the missenses look like they're pathogenic strongs.

223
00:13:10.892 --> 00:13:13.071
And if you look over here, that's a busy table.

224
00:13:13.211 --> 00:13:17.152
I'm only going to focus on one number, which is that how many of the missenses are

225
00:13:17.192 --> 00:13:18.712
in the pathogenic strong category?

226
00:13:19.092 --> 00:13:22.692
The answer is 502, which is about 10%, 11% of all the

227
00:13:22.732 --> 00:13:23.612
missense variants.

228
00:13:24.412 --> 00:13:27.692
That's a huge number because if you go into ClinVar today, you only find about

229
00:13:29.112 --> 00:13:32.732
30 to 50 missense variants that are considered pathogenic strong or

230
00:13:33.112 --> 00:13:34.022
likely pathogenic.

231
00:13:35.232 --> 00:13:38.132
Here, there's 500 in this assay. Okay?

232
00:13:38.152 --> 00:13:41.292
But again, this is function. This is not clinical classification.

233
00:13:41.552 --> 00:13:44.232
That's the difference. So keep in mind, this is still only function.

234
00:13:47.052 --> 00:13:50.992
Now, one of the major important things with a MAVE, when you do a MAVE, is what's

235
00:13:51.012 --> 00:13:53.022
the performance of your MAVE to known standards?

236
00:13:53.912 --> 00:13:57.762
And I mentioned that we model the data on standards, but we still have to

237
00:13:57.792 --> 00:13:59.352
assess the performance on standards.

238
00:13:59.452 --> 00:14:02.892
So we actually, with BRCA2, were able to come up with a series of different

239
00:14:02.972 --> 00:14:06.852
standards. These are known pathogenics in ClinVar, in the ClinVar

240
00:14:06.892 --> 00:14:10.812
database, all the way down to a different DNA repair assay that we

241
00:14:10.832 --> 00:14:13.912
do in our lab, and we've published hundreds of variants using this assay.

242
00:14:14.632 --> 00:14:17.832
So we had different metrics that we could actually use to assess the sensitivity

243
00:14:17.852 --> 00:14:21.092
and specificity so that the data wasn't circular. Right?

244
00:14:21.432 --> 00:14:24.631
You want it to be independent of how you originally trained the model.

245
00:14:25.512 --> 00:14:28.992
And if you look over here at the sensitivity and specificity, we're above 93% to

246
00:14:29.032 --> 00:14:32.832
95% in all of those categories. So it really does

247
00:14:32.872 --> 00:14:36.612
look like the MAVE worked really quite well and matches up with what's known about

248
00:14:36.622 --> 00:14:38.572
this protein and this gene.

249
00:14:39.572 --> 00:14:42.392
One take home message here, however, is that MAVEs are not perfect.

250
00:14:43.292 --> 00:14:47.272
There is error in MAVEs, and you can see that there's a few percent that are

251
00:14:48.012 --> 00:14:49.132
differential, that are wrong,

252
00:14:50.132 --> 00:14:52.692
and that makes sense. We expect that in a biological system.

253
00:14:53.472 --> 00:14:55.492
Perhaps more replicates would have fixed that.

254
00:14:56.572 --> 00:14:58.552
Addition of other data might fix that.

255
00:14:58.592 --> 00:15:01.312
But certainly there's more work to be done to sort that out.

256
00:15:04.932 --> 00:15:08.661
Now that we've done a functional assay and we can calibrate all these data and

257
00:15:08.872 --> 00:15:12.212
look at all these variants, the next question is, well, is it actually clinically

258
00:15:12.272 --> 00:15:12.712
meaningful?

259
00:15:14.472 --> 00:15:17.272
So one way to do that was to look at risk, simple risk.

260
00:15:17.362 --> 00:15:19.692
So this is a case-control association study.

261
00:15:21.112 --> 00:15:24.352
This is data provided to us by clinical collaborators.

262
00:15:24.412 --> 00:15:27.032
This is Ambry Genetics in particular.

263
00:15:27.052 --> 00:15:30.232
And we were able to take all the variants like these pstrongs, all those missenses

264
00:15:30.252 --> 00:15:33.952
that were pstrong in the prior slide that I showed you, and run them through a

265
00:15:34.012 --> 00:15:36.612
case-control association study, and you get 4.5.

266
00:15:37.472 --> 00:15:40.072
Truncating mutations are coming in around 5.5.

267
00:15:41.392 --> 00:15:44.772
So okay, they're a little bit different, but the confidence intervals overlap, so

268
00:15:44.812 --> 00:15:46.372
we can't actually say that they're different.

269
00:15:46.732 --> 00:15:50.552
But the important take home message here is that as a pool, all

270
00:15:50.572 --> 00:15:52.692
these pstrong variants are high risk.

271
00:15:53.252 --> 00:15:56.752
They definitely increase the risk of breast and ovarian cancer, as you can see down

272
00:15:56.772 --> 00:16:00.622
below. So this sort of confirms that the assay, on a

273
00:16:00.632 --> 00:16:03.402
global level at least, is giving us the right results.

274
00:16:03.472 --> 00:16:05.552
It's matching up with the clinical phenotypes.

275
00:16:10.092 --> 00:16:12.512
This is just relating back to the ACMG model.

276
00:16:12.592 --> 00:16:16.532
We wanted to then-- the other way of looking at this clinically is can you run them

277
00:16:16.572 --> 00:16:20.322
through ClinGen ACMG models and classify them as

278
00:16:20.352 --> 00:16:23.332
pathogenic or likely pathogenic or benign, likely benign?

279
00:16:24.672 --> 00:16:27.552
So that's really the goal. For a clinician to be able to use the data, you have to

280
00:16:27.592 --> 00:16:31.252
get to that point. So this is sort of the ACMG model that we

281
00:16:31.392 --> 00:16:35.052
use. There are two what we call VCEPs, variant curation

282
00:16:35.112 --> 00:16:37.992
expert panels, that have been set up. One is for BRCA one and two.

283
00:16:38.192 --> 00:16:42.112
Another is for all the other predisposition genes for breast,

284
00:16:42.172 --> 00:16:45.572
ovarian, and pancreatic. And those two groups work on trying to

285
00:16:45.632 --> 00:16:48.262
classify variants with all these different measures.

286
00:16:48.292 --> 00:16:51.852
And you can see them listed out down below, in silico predictions,

287
00:16:51.952 --> 00:16:55.782
case-control data, functional data is in there, et

288
00:16:56.172 --> 00:16:59.712
cetera. You can combine them all together with a series of points to come up with

289
00:16:59.772 --> 00:17:00.752
classifications.

290
00:17:01.652 --> 00:17:03.772
And that's what this Sankey plot actually is

291
00:17:05.212 --> 00:17:08.613
or this alluvial plot as some people like to call it. What are you looking at?

292
00:17:08.652 --> 00:17:12.232
It's a very busy slide, but basically it's the five different types of variants

293
00:17:13.152 --> 00:17:16.412
on the vertical axis there, and then all the little functional categories that we

294
00:17:16.472 --> 00:17:20.333
have within each type of variant. So pathogenic strongs, the benign

295
00:17:20.392 --> 00:17:22.833
strongs, the seven categories in each group.

296
00:17:23.712 --> 00:17:27.502
And then having taken that function, we integrate it with all the other data in the

297
00:17:27.572 --> 00:17:31.002
ACMG model, and here's your final ACMG classification.

298
00:17:32.452 --> 00:17:35.712
You can see they break down into those five categories that I mentioned, the likely

299
00:17:35.722 --> 00:17:39.132
benigns and benigns, the likely pathogenics and pathogenics,

300
00:17:39.712 --> 00:17:43.412
and then the VUS in the middle. And so starting with 7,000 variants,

301
00:17:43.792 --> 00:17:46.412
we end up with only 608 that remain as VUS

302
00:17:47.232 --> 00:17:48.012
in this experiment.

303
00:17:48.932 --> 00:17:51.232
So you've taken care of over 90% of your variants.

304
00:17:52.212 --> 00:17:54.842
So this is the beauty of all these models. They connect together now.

305
00:17:55.292 --> 00:17:59.012
You go from this large functional screen all the way to clinical

306
00:17:59.072 --> 00:18:02.192
classification in one swath.

307
00:18:07.392 --> 00:18:10.152
So that's BRCA2. You can see how effective that looks.

308
00:18:10.912 --> 00:18:13.812
It's really quite impressive how it worked out.

309
00:18:14.452 --> 00:18:17.092
But MAVEs have been done now for some of these other genes that I mentioned at the

310
00:18:17.132 --> 00:18:19.992
beginning. BRCA1 was done years ago, as I said.

311
00:18:20.972 --> 00:18:22.512
There's been some follow-up studies on that.

312
00:18:22.552 --> 00:18:22.812
There's a

313
00:18:23.712 --> 00:18:24.792
meta archive paper

314
00:18:25.912 --> 00:18:29.862
from a group in the UKWhere instead of doing it in Hap1s, they

315
00:18:29.922 --> 00:18:32.862
now did it in primary mammary epithelial cells.

316
00:18:33.542 --> 00:18:37.322
So these are cells from the breast rather than a Hap1 cell, which is actually a

317
00:18:37.362 --> 00:18:38.402
human leukemia line.

318
00:18:39.502 --> 00:18:42.722
So if you're going to study the effect on breast and ovarian cancer, maybe you need

319
00:18:42.742 --> 00:18:45.842
to be using the right cell type. That was the rationale behind their study.

320
00:18:46.762 --> 00:18:50.702
And they actually found a lot of discrepancies in their results for HMX

321
00:18:50.762 --> 00:18:54.342
versus Hap1s. And I think the jury's still out on what that means

322
00:18:54.702 --> 00:18:57.772
and how to integrate those two results together.

323
00:18:58.082 --> 00:19:01.662
We're still thinking about that. But there may need to be

324
00:19:01.702 --> 00:19:03.552
recalibration of functional assays.

325
00:19:04.022 --> 00:19:06.122
It could be that the whole register is just off,

326
00:19:07.042 --> 00:19:09.122
and maybe they just shift relative to one another.

327
00:19:09.162 --> 00:19:12.722
The efficacy within one cell type could be different to the other, but as long as

328
00:19:12.742 --> 00:19:15.182
it's proportional, maybe it's reading out the same result.

329
00:19:16.082 --> 00:19:18.842
That's to be determined. BRCA2, as I just showed you,

330
00:19:19.742 --> 00:19:21.462
about 14% were non-functional.

331
00:19:22.302 --> 00:19:25.202
PALB2 was recently published in "Nature Communications."

332
00:19:26.022 --> 00:19:29.422
Only 5% are pathogenic, likely pathogenic in that setting,

333
00:19:29.762 --> 00:19:33.502
40% intermediate. So a lot to be done there really to resolve some of

334
00:19:33.562 --> 00:19:33.802
that.

335
00:19:34.702 --> 00:19:38.682
ATM was published in early 2025 by a group from South Korea.

336
00:19:39.582 --> 00:19:42.932
All 63 exons, a monumental amount of work really to get through that

337
00:19:42.962 --> 00:19:43.762
gene.

338
00:19:45.382 --> 00:19:48.942
But they actually found about 23%, 25% of the missense

339
00:19:49.042 --> 00:19:51.462
variants looked like they were knocking out activity.

340
00:19:52.482 --> 00:19:56.162
And then finally, CHEK2 has been published as a series of yeast viability screens.

341
00:19:56.682 --> 00:19:59.902
There's some human studies that are underway right now, but they're not published

342
00:19:59.962 --> 00:20:03.062
yet. But the yeast viability screens are suggesting maybe

343
00:20:03.102 --> 00:20:05.902
15% of the missenses are pathogenic.

344
00:20:06.502 --> 00:20:08.642
So I think you can see here that every gene is different, right?

345
00:20:08.722 --> 00:20:12.572
These numbers are bouncing around from 5% up to 25% in terms of

346
00:20:12.622 --> 00:20:15.502
how many missenses would be pathogenic.

347
00:20:15.562 --> 00:20:19.122
And a number of years ago, there was a few publications and white papers

348
00:20:19.162 --> 00:20:22.862
suggesting that maybe only 2% to 5% of all VUS would be pathogenic.

349
00:20:23.202 --> 00:20:27.102
It's clearly not true. You can see from the data here that there can

350
00:20:27.122 --> 00:20:30.762
be very, very high loads of pathogenicity in some of these genes, up to

351
00:20:30.922 --> 00:20:31.762
25%.

352
00:20:34.082 --> 00:20:36.962
So let's now talk, just in the last couple of minutes, let's talk about

353
00:20:37.762 --> 00:20:38.381
combining

354
00:20:39.202 --> 00:20:43.152
MAIVs. So as I mentioned, now as more and more work is being done in this

355
00:20:43.202 --> 00:20:47.002
field, we're finding two or three or four MAIVs in

356
00:20:47.182 --> 00:20:49.602
different genes. How can we put those together?

357
00:20:50.962 --> 00:20:52.542
Well, there's a couple of different models here, right?

358
00:20:52.662 --> 00:20:55.042
We have to think about what it actually means when we do two

359
00:20:55.082 --> 00:20:58.822
MAIVs. Are they two MAIVs for exactly the same

360
00:20:58.862 --> 00:21:01.722
function? So like BRCA2, let's say a DNA repair assay.

361
00:21:02.642 --> 00:21:06.352
So were two MAIVs done, both measuring DNA repair activity in

362
00:21:06.362 --> 00:21:10.102
BRCA2? If that's true, then you could probably combine the data at a

363
00:21:10.122 --> 00:21:11.202
fairly elemental level.

364
00:21:12.622 --> 00:21:15.762
But if it's two MAIVs done under totally different conditions,

365
00:21:16.602 --> 00:21:20.422
so you might have added a drug on one or given a different dose of drug or

366
00:21:20.482 --> 00:21:24.451
done different time points, you've got to think carefully about what the results

367
00:21:24.502 --> 00:21:26.582
mean. You can't just throw them together, I think.

368
00:21:26.622 --> 00:21:29.671
We really have to calibrate those data relative to one another.

369
00:21:30.522 --> 00:21:32.082
What happens if they're in different cell types?

370
00:21:32.142 --> 00:21:34.482
I mentioned the BRCA1 result that's in MedArchive.

371
00:21:35.042 --> 00:21:38.261
That's really confusing, the result that they've produced to this point.

372
00:21:39.262 --> 00:21:40.442
And we need to think about that.

373
00:21:42.002 --> 00:21:45.222
I think most of us would agree that there could definitely be splicing differences

374
00:21:45.282 --> 00:21:47.742
and protein stability differences in different cell types.

375
00:21:48.462 --> 00:21:51.662
So that might be one of the underlying reasons why there are differences, but there

376
00:21:51.702 --> 00:21:52.262
may be others.

377
00:21:54.022 --> 00:21:57.842
And then if you're measuring totally different functions, that could be problematic

378
00:21:57.902 --> 00:21:58.242
as well.

379
00:21:59.782 --> 00:22:00.162
And so,

380
00:22:01.322 --> 00:22:04.842
in a setting where you have totally different functions or totally different cell

381
00:22:04.882 --> 00:22:07.082
types, you really do have to be careful.

382
00:22:07.142 --> 00:22:10.662
And in that situation, we may not want to do a combination of the MAIVs.

383
00:22:10.782 --> 00:22:14.062
We really may want to treat them as completely independent and never merge them

384
00:22:14.862 --> 00:22:17.642
because they're really measuring totally different things. Okay?

385
00:22:18.122 --> 00:22:20.602
Just keep that in mind. It's always a warning sign

386
00:22:21.762 --> 00:22:22.982
associated with some of these things.

387
00:22:23.902 --> 00:22:26.202
So there was a nice paper

388
00:22:27.562 --> 00:22:29.702
published here by Calhoun. Well, he's not published yet.

389
00:22:29.762 --> 00:22:32.742
It's again, in the archives from Calhoun.

390
00:22:32.782 --> 00:22:34.162
This is a white paper from the

391
00:22:35.162 --> 00:22:38.942
AIV group or the MAIV group. There's a sort of a consortium been put together

392
00:22:39.062 --> 00:22:40.662
to look at MAIVs.

393
00:22:41.962 --> 00:22:45.562
And they came up with a series of steps that you should

394
00:22:45.602 --> 00:22:48.891
consider if you're going to put these combinations of these things

395
00:22:48.902 --> 00:22:49.902
together.

396
00:22:51.462 --> 00:22:54.422
So one, of course, is to map them onto the same transcript of the gene.

397
00:22:54.622 --> 00:22:56.352
I think that's just sensible, right?

398
00:22:56.622 --> 00:22:58.802
You're looking at the same-- It's not apples and oranges.

399
00:22:58.842 --> 00:23:01.122
They are actually the same coding regions.

400
00:23:02.482 --> 00:23:05.562
Use only commonly evaluated variants.

401
00:23:05.622 --> 00:23:06.962
Now, that's an interesting idea, right?

402
00:23:07.002 --> 00:23:10.752
So if you restrict to only the variants that are done in both of the MAIVs,

403
00:23:11.822 --> 00:23:14.102
what are you losing there? Are you leaving out a lot of data?

404
00:23:14.162 --> 00:23:17.582
And I'll show you an example for BRCA2 in a few minutes where that actually becomes

405
00:23:17.622 --> 00:23:18.302
quite important.

406
00:23:19.542 --> 00:23:21.822
Should you be allowing for the missing data in some way?

407
00:23:24.162 --> 00:23:26.662
Consider excluding candidate splicing variants.

408
00:23:26.722 --> 00:23:28.522
Some of these assays are done with cDNAs.

409
00:23:30.362 --> 00:23:32.822
Some of them are deep into the introns.

410
00:23:32.882 --> 00:23:34.482
Some don't have any introns at all, right?

411
00:23:34.582 --> 00:23:38.422
So you may have differences in the MAIVs in terms of the ability to catch splicing

412
00:23:38.482 --> 00:23:41.022
effects in canonical splice sites.

413
00:23:41.482 --> 00:23:45.382
And then can you take the data and transform it and rescale

414
00:23:45.422 --> 00:23:48.772
it so that the two experiments are actually on the same basic footprint,

415
00:23:49.422 --> 00:23:51.592
so that you could actually combine the data a little bit better?

416
00:23:52.172 --> 00:23:53.552
So all of these fairly detailed--

417
00:23:54.762 --> 00:23:57.422
people can make assumptions about this stuff, but I think we really have to

418
00:23:57.462 --> 00:24:00.352
evaluate them very carefully before we put data together.

419
00:24:01.862 --> 00:24:05.682
And in that white paper then, they just went through a whole-- I encourage you all

420
00:24:05.722 --> 00:24:07.922
to go read it. As I said, it's in the archives.

421
00:24:08.642 --> 00:24:11.142
It's really worth a read if you're interested in this field.

422
00:24:11.812 --> 00:24:12.022
But they

423
00:24:13.022 --> 00:24:16.082
walk through a series of different potential models for combining the data

424
00:24:16.162 --> 00:24:16.502
together,

425
00:24:17.862 --> 00:24:19.442
and for reevaluating the performance.

426
00:24:20.122 --> 00:24:24.082
And they do come back then with one example, which is p53, the

427
00:24:24.122 --> 00:24:27.902
TP53 gene. And they basically take data from

428
00:24:28.102 --> 00:24:31.482
four different functional screens of p53, and they put it all

429
00:24:31.502 --> 00:24:35.458
together.And interestingly, the model that wins in the end was

430
00:24:35.498 --> 00:24:36.358
a random forest.

431
00:24:37.438 --> 00:24:39.338
So basically, it's a probability-based model.

432
00:24:39.368 --> 00:24:42.638
They put all the data in together, and the model sort of figures out what is the

433
00:24:42.678 --> 00:24:46.418
right combination. But it was vastly superior to the other methods.

434
00:24:46.498 --> 00:24:49.378
As you can see here, this sort of teal-colored peak.

435
00:24:50.458 --> 00:24:54.098
And so that was their final take-home message is that

436
00:24:55.178 --> 00:24:58.798
a combined MAIV of four different assays using a random

437
00:24:58.858 --> 00:25:02.038
forest was really the right way to go for P53.

438
00:25:04.118 --> 00:25:07.858
So that's a success story. That was a great example, but what about other genes?

439
00:25:08.778 --> 00:25:11.938
So I want to tell you a little bit about a study we just published on

440
00:25:12.158 --> 00:25:14.848
BRCA2, where we did try to do something similar.

441
00:25:16.598 --> 00:25:20.038
So just to give you some background on the two MAIV experiments I'm talking about,

442
00:25:20.118 --> 00:25:23.958
one is the experiment I mentioned that I just described for BRCA2,

443
00:25:23.998 --> 00:25:26.818
which is our own study in the human HAP1 line.

444
00:25:27.898 --> 00:25:31.878
And then the other was actually in mouse embryonic stem cells done

445
00:25:31.898 --> 00:25:33.398
by Shime Sharan at the NCI.

446
00:25:35.698 --> 00:25:39.198
Again, using a viability assay. So at least we were using the same basic readout,

447
00:25:39.438 --> 00:25:42.538
which was viability, but two totally different cell types.

448
00:25:44.098 --> 00:25:47.478
Very similar coverage, but there were some differences.

449
00:25:48.098 --> 00:25:51.798
And if you look at our assay relative to standards, we were at 93%

450
00:25:51.858 --> 00:25:55.338
sensitivity and 95% specificity relative to the known standards.

451
00:25:55.938 --> 00:25:59.118
They were just a little bit lower. But in general, the performance of the two

452
00:25:59.198 --> 00:26:03.038
assays were similar. Okay? So then the question was: Could we

453
00:26:03.078 --> 00:26:03.878
combine the data?

454
00:26:05.878 --> 00:26:09.138
So the way we went ahead was four different models.

455
00:26:09.198 --> 00:26:11.858
We wanted to assess really all possible approaches here.

456
00:26:11.898 --> 00:26:15.798
So one was just what I call a concordance model that anybody in

457
00:26:15.818 --> 00:26:18.108
this room could do. Take the two data sets,

458
00:26:18.978 --> 00:26:22.878
slam them together, and just take the variants that are commonly assessed

459
00:26:22.918 --> 00:26:25.538
by both methods and see if there's consistency.

460
00:26:25.618 --> 00:26:27.008
So just look for the consistency.

461
00:26:27.938 --> 00:26:30.398
Did both assays show it as a benign effect?

462
00:26:30.438 --> 00:26:33.678
Did both assays show it as a non-functional effect, right?

463
00:26:34.098 --> 00:26:35.718
That's a fairly easy result.

464
00:26:37.318 --> 00:26:40.238
And then only classify the variants that have concordance.

465
00:26:40.438 --> 00:26:43.978
If something is discordant between two assays, you throw it away because you don't

466
00:26:43.998 --> 00:26:45.758
know who has the right answer. Okay?

467
00:26:47.118 --> 00:26:50.718
So in this concordance model for BRCA2, we end up only evaluating

468
00:26:50.818 --> 00:26:54.698
80% of the variants. We lose 20% because of all these caveats that I

469
00:26:54.758 --> 00:26:57.698
just explained to you. They end up getting dropped out.

470
00:26:58.138 --> 00:27:01.598
And that's a problem, right? Because when you're trying to address all possible

471
00:27:01.678 --> 00:27:05.278
variants for clinical purposes, you really want to do as close to

472
00:27:05.338 --> 00:27:09.318
100% as possible. Losing 20% of the variants is really not

473
00:27:09.358 --> 00:27:09.777
a good thing.

474
00:27:11.678 --> 00:27:15.238
The other way we did it was we actually, because the two assays were very similar

475
00:27:15.298 --> 00:27:16.578
and they were looking at viability,

476
00:27:17.898 --> 00:27:21.858
we were able to actually scale the two experiments together and then take their raw

477
00:27:21.898 --> 00:27:23.858
data and our raw data and put it together

478
00:27:25.158 --> 00:27:28.978
and treat it all as raw data. So we ended up with five experimental points from the

479
00:27:29.018 --> 00:27:32.558
two combined assays, and then we ran our VarCall model.

480
00:27:33.598 --> 00:27:35.238
So that's what we call the integrated model.

481
00:27:35.478 --> 00:27:39.258
You're actually using the raw data from both experiments to look at consistency.

482
00:27:40.658 --> 00:27:42.768
And that ends up doing the vast majority of the variants.

483
00:27:42.798 --> 00:27:46.518
It's something like 94%, 95% of the variants get captured in that experiment.

484
00:27:47.618 --> 00:27:51.018
And then these other ones are just other models. That's a VarCall experiment.

485
00:27:51.318 --> 00:27:55.258
There's another method called GMM, which is another way of just analyzing the data

486
00:27:55.318 --> 00:27:59.018
by probability, and then concordance of the GMM and the

487
00:27:59.058 --> 00:28:01.818
VarCalls, right? So we're just looking at four different methods.

488
00:28:02.598 --> 00:28:04.538
And here's sort of a busy

489
00:28:05.578 --> 00:28:09.518
slide here, but let me point out that the one on the left is based on ClinVar.

490
00:28:10.378 --> 00:28:13.878
So there's a number of known pathogenic and known benign variants in ClinVar.

491
00:28:13.938 --> 00:28:16.948
We use those as standards to evaluate these four models.

492
00:28:17.718 --> 00:28:21.098
And then the other one was this homologous recombination DNA repair assay that I

493
00:28:21.138 --> 00:28:21.778
mentioned earlier

494
00:28:22.698 --> 00:28:23.997
that we've done as a standalone

495
00:28:24.838 --> 00:28:28.488
study, and we'd done enough variants in there that we could use them as

496
00:28:28.558 --> 00:28:31.818
standards in this assay, right? And so when you line them all up, what you're

497
00:28:31.858 --> 00:28:34.958
looking for is how well does the integrated VarCall model do?

498
00:28:35.598 --> 00:28:36.398
You can see them here.

499
00:28:37.458 --> 00:28:41.428
There are some peaks that are higher, but no model really does better

500
00:28:41.998 --> 00:28:44.458
in terms of getting the two peaks close together.

501
00:28:44.498 --> 00:28:47.898
You want both sensitivity and specificity to be working well here.

502
00:28:49.527 --> 00:28:50.618
Specificity being

503
00:28:52.138 --> 00:28:56.048
false positives, right? So if you have a benign variant and you mistakenly

504
00:28:56.138 --> 00:28:59.518
call it a pathogenic variant, that's a real problem in the clinical world

505
00:29:00.158 --> 00:29:02.758
because now you're potentially telling a patient that they have a pathogenic

506
00:29:02.838 --> 00:29:04.058
variant when in fact they don't.

507
00:29:05.238 --> 00:29:08.918
So in clinical assays, the specificity is oftentimes more

508
00:29:08.938 --> 00:29:11.338
important than the sensitivity for that very reason.

509
00:29:11.378 --> 00:29:13.118
You don't want to make a mistake. Okay?

510
00:29:13.878 --> 00:29:15.818
So that's why we want both peaks close together.

511
00:29:16.538 --> 00:29:18.718
In the HR standards, we see a better separation.

512
00:29:18.778 --> 00:29:22.758
You can see that the consistency there for the integrated model looks better.

513
00:29:23.618 --> 00:29:27.218
So we ended up landing on the integrated model and said that was the best approach.

514
00:29:28.318 --> 00:29:31.778
And then this is that Sankey plot where we look at the types of variants,

515
00:29:32.658 --> 00:29:36.418
we look at the results of the functional integrated model, and then we go all the

516
00:29:36.438 --> 00:29:39.198
way to ACMG classification again, as I showed before.

517
00:29:40.098 --> 00:29:43.158
What do you end up with this time? Now we have 396

518
00:29:44.458 --> 00:29:45.238
that are VUS.

519
00:29:46.118 --> 00:29:46.398
So

520
00:29:47.258 --> 00:29:51.158
we're still measuring over 95% of all the variants, and yet

521
00:29:51.238 --> 00:29:55.018
our VUS rate has dropped down to 396, whereas before it was

522
00:29:55.058 --> 00:29:55.818
over 500.

523
00:29:56.698 --> 00:30:00.198
So we did tighten up the data, it did clean the data, and it

524
00:30:00.238 --> 00:30:02.858
resolved more of the variants at the same time.

525
00:30:02.898 --> 00:30:06.658
So the take-home message here is that the combined data set is

526
00:30:06.678 --> 00:30:10.578
better than any individual data set, as you might expect, but it's

527
00:30:10.618 --> 00:30:13.478
nice to see the proof on the page here.

528
00:30:16.498 --> 00:30:20.298
And then to just verify that at the clinical level, we did the case-control

529
00:30:20.778 --> 00:30:24.658
risk analysis again. And sure enough, you can see the peaks here or

530
00:30:25.738 --> 00:30:26.438
the dots here on the

531
00:30:28.098 --> 00:30:31.678
plot here. You're seeing that these pathogenic strong variants from the

532
00:30:31.718 --> 00:30:35.438
combined model are behaving just like the protein-truncating

533
00:30:35.458 --> 00:30:38.128
variants. So everything was working fine in that

534
00:30:38.158 --> 00:30:42.010
regard.I will say, however, that there are other

535
00:30:42.050 --> 00:30:45.630
functional assays out there. I've just showed you the results for two big

536
00:30:45.690 --> 00:30:49.290
MAVEs, but there's other assays that I won't get into in detail,

537
00:30:49.400 --> 00:30:52.960
but these are much smaller. They've only done a few hundred at a time.

538
00:30:53.390 --> 00:30:56.630
But they're still valuable data, and we'd like to be able to use them.

539
00:30:56.650 --> 00:31:00.290
And so there's a presentation tomorrow from Alvaro Monteiro that I encourage you to

540
00:31:00.330 --> 00:31:04.260
look at, where he actually talks about the integration of huge numbers of

541
00:31:04.290 --> 00:31:08.130
functional assays for both BRCA1 and two, and how you can put all the data

542
00:31:08.140 --> 00:31:11.830
together from many different types of assays, not just from MAVEs.

543
00:31:12.170 --> 00:31:15.190
Okay, so if you're interested, I encourage you to go attend that.

544
00:31:16.490 --> 00:31:17.730
So let me give a summary here.

545
00:31:19.770 --> 00:31:23.130
So MAVEs are wonderful for providing detailed functional data for many

546
00:31:23.170 --> 00:31:25.310
variants. Functional data, okay?

547
00:31:26.050 --> 00:31:29.770
But then you can integrate the data into the ClinGen ACMG

548
00:31:29.810 --> 00:31:30.910
models, as I showed you.

549
00:31:31.910 --> 00:31:35.330
And that's proven very effective for reclassification of, in

550
00:31:35.370 --> 00:31:39.350
our assay at least, over 95% of the VUS in the

551
00:31:39.390 --> 00:31:40.210
region of interest.

552
00:31:41.310 --> 00:31:45.270
And that's the result there. So where

553
00:31:45.330 --> 00:31:48.090
multiple MAVEs do exist, a variety of methods

554
00:31:49.010 --> 00:31:51.570
for combining the MAVEs can be used.

555
00:31:51.870 --> 00:31:55.450
I just gave you one example. We saw the P53 example, we saw the

556
00:31:55.470 --> 00:31:58.190
BRCA2 example. There's many other ways of doing it.

557
00:31:59.350 --> 00:32:00.570
Every combined MAVE

558
00:32:01.510 --> 00:32:03.850
experiment is just going to be totally different.

559
00:32:03.870 --> 00:32:07.670
It's going to be unique, and you try to put those together as best you can,

560
00:32:08.050 --> 00:32:10.190
but you have to know something about your disease and your gene.

561
00:32:11.650 --> 00:32:15.570
The P53 approach was really interesting to see

562
00:32:15.610 --> 00:32:17.830
how that worked out so well with a random forest model.

563
00:32:19.490 --> 00:32:20.950
I told you about the two MAVE studies.

564
00:32:21.770 --> 00:32:25.390
And then the take home message from all of this is that combining MAVEs, individual

565
00:32:25.450 --> 00:32:29.310
MAVEs and combining MAVEs, are really expected to have

566
00:32:29.390 --> 00:32:29.850
dramatic

567
00:32:30.850 --> 00:32:34.290
impacts on improved diagnostics and risk assessment for patients.

568
00:32:34.360 --> 00:32:36.520
And that's what it's all about. It's about the patients in the end.

569
00:32:37.230 --> 00:32:40.440
It's not just a genetics exercise. There's a purpose behind this.

570
00:32:41.170 --> 00:32:41.590
So,

571
00:32:42.570 --> 00:32:46.250
I will stop there, and I will happily take some questions for a few minutes before

572
00:32:46.290 --> 00:32:47.170
I hand over to Jacob.

573
00:33:03.950 --> 00:33:04.970
Good, we have one customer.

574
00:33:05.550 --> 00:33:06.110
Hi, Dr. Couch.

