00:33:16.670 --> 00:33:17.050
So there's

581
00:33:17.970 --> 00:33:21.850
more recent work over the last, well, six-ish years about its

582
00:33:21.930 --> 00:33:22.650
sensitivity,

583
00:33:24.070 --> 00:33:27.930
or hypersensitivity is more due to single-strand gaps-

584
00:33:28.270 --> 00:33:28.370
Yeah

585
00:33:28.470 --> 00:33:32.120
... other than, say, HDR. So I'm curious if that's something you guys have thought

586
00:33:32.150 --> 00:33:35.290
about testing these variants in terms of the numbers.

587
00:33:35.310 --> 00:33:38.379
Yeah. And there's another paper that has come out related to what you're just

588
00:33:38.490 --> 00:33:41.910
saying. There's a paper came out from Katerina Schlacker at MD Anderson

589
00:33:42.090 --> 00:33:45.840
showing replication fork effects, which is kind of related to what you're talking

590
00:33:45.870 --> 00:33:46.650
about there.

591
00:33:48.270 --> 00:33:52.220
In her paper, she shows one particular variant way down

592
00:33:52.230 --> 00:33:55.780
at the C terminus of BRCA2 that is outside this DNA-binding domain that has

593
00:33:55.830 --> 00:33:59.770
separation of function. It impacts replication forks but doesn't impact

594
00:33:59.930 --> 00:34:01.410
homologous recombination repair.

595
00:34:02.330 --> 00:34:05.910
But it obviously brings up the question of whether all of these

596
00:34:05.950 --> 00:34:09.710
variants are impacting replication stress as well

597
00:34:09.770 --> 00:34:13.190
as double-strand break repair, right? And so that has to be evaluated.

598
00:34:13.250 --> 00:34:16.290
So we're trying to build assays now that would measure that.

599
00:34:17.190 --> 00:34:21.091
There's a sort of a colorimetric

600
00:34:21.150 --> 00:34:24.111
assay that potentially could be used to do that in a high-throughput method.

601
00:34:25.011 --> 00:34:28.290
So it's definitely a question, and it relates to some of the things I talked about,

602
00:34:28.370 --> 00:34:28.841
which is that,

603
00:34:29.670 --> 00:34:32.730
are you measuring two different functions? Are you really measuring just one?

604
00:34:32.930 --> 00:34:36.450
It's really quite important to be certain that you're focusing on one

605
00:34:36.730 --> 00:34:37.190
outcome.

606
00:34:38.470 --> 00:34:38.870
Thank you.

607
00:34:39.031 --> 00:34:39.350
Okay.

608
00:34:42.270 --> 00:34:44.571
Can I have a very short,

609
00:34:46.011 --> 00:34:49.071
not question, but I'm doing some clinical

