the genome, adding either a short random sequence

954
00:53:46.884 --> 00:53:49.624
or what we often do is to add a bunch of silent mutations.

955
00:53:49.674 --> 00:53:53.604
This is, again, in the context of a cDNA-based screen, so we're not worried

956
00:53:53.644 --> 00:53:55.384
that these silent mutations are going to impair

957
00:53:56.604 --> 00:53:57.184
splicing.

958
00:53:58.324 --> 00:54:02.304
But we add these in cis in line with the actual missense mutations that we've made.

959
00:54:02.644 --> 00:54:05.824
So what is this bias? Or equivalently, what is having an

960
00:54:05.904 --> 00:54:09.144
off-site barcode bias? Well, it gives us the ability to

961
00:54:09.204 --> 00:54:11.664
do statistics on the effects that we measure.

962
00:54:12.264 --> 00:54:16.124
So if we don't have a barcode, in the absence of a barcode, we are just counting

963
00:54:16.364 --> 00:54:19.504
using... The sequencer is really just a fancy and expensive counting machine.

964
00:54:19.544 --> 00:54:23.134
We're counting how often do we see a given mutation at the end of the

965
00:54:23.224 --> 00:54:24.684
experiment versus at the beginning.

966
00:54:25.304 --> 00:54:29.244
But really our hope is that that mutation has been integrated independently into

967
00:54:29.284 --> 00:54:33.184
cells thousands or tens of thousands of times. Right?

968
00:54:33.194 --> 00:54:36.493
And so we would really like to have the individual counts of those initial

969
00:54:36.544 --> 00:54:39.564
integration events, and we'd love to be able to track them through the experiment.

970
00:54:40.464 --> 00:54:44.224
But if it's only the mutation of interest that we've made, those are all

971
00:54:44.924 --> 00:54:46.424
identical at the sequence level. Right?

972
00:54:46.804 --> 00:54:50.534
So adding a barcode or adding these inline silent mutations allows us to

973
00:54:50.564 --> 00:54:54.484
track them and do comparisons of distributions, and that can give

974
00:54:54.524 --> 00:54:57.744
us much finer resolution on the scores that we measure.

975
00:54:58.844 --> 00:55:01.504
Okay, so I'll talk a bit about the mismatch repair genes in Lynch syndrome.

976
00:55:01.544 --> 00:55:05.304
Probably doesn't need a ton of introduction to this group, but there are four

977
00:55:05.444 --> 00:55:08.844
core genes in the DNA mismatch repair pathway, the

978
00:55:08.884 --> 00:55:10.564
canonical branch of this pathway.

979
00:55:10.624 --> 00:55:13.744
And loss of function in any one of these four

980
00:55:14.264 --> 00:55:18.204
confers a greatly elevated risk for early onset colorectal and endometrial

981
00:55:18.284 --> 00:55:22.256
cancers. Overall prevalence is thought to beBetween 1

982
00:55:22.276 --> 00:55:25.906
in 270 to 1 in 300. And sort of as a consequence of this

983
00:55:26.996 --> 00:55:30.976
and the variable and relatively late age of onset

984
00:55:30.996 --> 00:55:34.376
for these cancers, there are probably on the order of a million

985
00:55:34.416 --> 00:55:37.276
carriers in the US alone who are unaware of their risk.

986
00:55:38.356 --> 00:55:41.966
Okay. And so, the lion's share then of

987
00:55:43.916 --> 00:55:47.696
variants that cannot be classified clinically and remain in this VUS

988
00:55:47.796 --> 00:55:51.216
pile are missense variants. And so they're again, sort

989
00:55:51.256 --> 00:55:54.356
of similar to the BRCA1, BRCA2

990
00:55:55.056 --> 00:55:55.556
genes.

991
00:55:56.456 --> 00:55:59.956
There are thousands of uncategorized

992
00:55:59.976 --> 00:56:03.836
VUSs and again, these are primarily missense across

993
00:56:03.856 --> 00:56:04.576
these four genes.

994
00:56:05.996 --> 00:56:09.336
So we can test these. How do we do that for mismatch repair genes?

995
00:56:10.336 --> 00:56:13.236
Kind of told you about the generic steps, but one of the key ingredients when

996
00:56:13.256 --> 00:56:17.086
you're setting out to do a MAVE is you've got to have a functional selection that

997
00:56:17.116 --> 00:56:20.076
tells you about the activity of the gene that you want to study.

998
00:56:20.096 --> 00:56:23.036
What's the activity of that protein? Different proteins do different things.

999
00:56:23.076 --> 00:56:24.636
So how do we do this for mismatch repair?

1000
00:56:25.196 --> 00:56:27.716
Turns out that mismatch repair is actually, this pathway is

1001
00:56:29.536 --> 00:56:33.036
almost without exception dispensable for growth

1002
00:56:33.596 --> 00:56:36.976
in culture in vitro, right? So we can culture cells that are knockouts

1003
00:56:38.036 --> 00:56:40.956
for any of these four genes, and they will grow at the same rate as their wild type

1004
00:56:41.396 --> 00:56:42.416
isogenic controls.

1005
00:56:43.356 --> 00:56:43.556
But,

1006
00:56:45.716 --> 00:56:49.556
depending on the MMR status in a cell line, this does expose different

1007
00:56:50.316 --> 00:56:51.936
sort of synthetic lethalities in vitro.

1008
00:56:51.966 --> 00:56:55.936
And the one that we take advantage of is treatment with a purine analog

1009
00:56:55.976 --> 00:56:59.236
called 6-thioguanine. And so this treatment with

1010
00:56:59.276 --> 00:57:03.016
this base analog is going to specifically kill

1011
00:57:03.136 --> 00:57:07.006
cells, sort of counterintuitively, it's going to kill cells that have

1012
00:57:07.056 --> 00:57:10.986
intact mismatch repair. So we can treat with 6TG, and this will enrich for

1013
00:57:11.056 --> 00:57:14.746
loss of function in that pathway. And then it's just off to the

1014
00:57:14.796 --> 00:57:16.915
races with sort of a similar

1015
00:57:17.876 --> 00:57:20.616
framework to what you've heard about. We're just flipping the sign.

1016
00:57:20.836 --> 00:57:24.576
So when we do these experiments and select with 6TG, the variants that are going to

1017
00:57:24.616 --> 00:57:28.536
enrich over the course of selection are going to be those that

1018
00:57:28.596 --> 00:57:29.956
are resistant to the 6TG,

1019
00:57:30.785 --> 00:57:33.396
and those are loss of function variants.

1020
00:57:33.476 --> 00:57:37.116
And those we believe will be the variants that are going to

1021
00:57:37.176 --> 00:57:38.446
correlate with pathogenicity.

1022
00:57:39.576 --> 00:57:43.536
So in the lab, we've now completed variant to function maps

1023
00:57:43.796 --> 00:57:43.956
of

1024
00:57:44.936 --> 00:57:48.776
all four of the key MMR genes. Only three would fit on the slide here, but this

1025
00:57:48.836 --> 00:57:52.616
adds up to over 73,000 variants. And again, sort

1026
00:57:52.656 --> 00:57:55.336
of showing these as a heat map where I've

1027
00:57:56.216 --> 00:57:59.625
arrayed them out from one end of the protein to the other.

1028
00:57:59.656 --> 00:58:02.595
Each column corresponding to a single codon, each row

1029
00:58:02.696 --> 00:58:06.676
corresponding to one of the different 19 mutant

1030
00:58:06.736 --> 00:58:09.565
amino acids, and then the wild type, of course, for a total of 20.

1031
00:58:10.216 --> 00:58:13.296
And the color of each cell representing the degree of

1032
00:58:14.076 --> 00:58:17.856
functional abnormality. So red, more and more red meaning more and more abnormal.

1033
00:58:18.796 --> 00:58:22.736
Couple of quality control checks that we do when we're running MAVEs and kind

1034
00:58:22.776 --> 00:58:26.446
of standard to do is that you'd expect to see a

1035
00:58:26.556 --> 00:58:29.196
strong... Well, not only should you see the truncating variants are

1036
00:58:30.436 --> 00:58:31.976
highly abnormal in the assay, and for

1037
00:58:33.256 --> 00:58:36.356
a number of reasons, those aren't included in for these genes specifically.

1038
00:58:36.416 --> 00:58:39.836
But sort of the next best thing and a great thing to always do is to look at the

1039
00:58:39.876 --> 00:58:43.856
proline bar. So you should get a strong ribbon of signal

1040
00:58:43.916 --> 00:58:47.596
for loss of function when you make substitutions to

1041
00:58:47.636 --> 00:58:50.556
proline within ordered regions of proteins, right?

1042
00:58:50.636 --> 00:58:54.096
These are generally highly destabilizing the secondary structure.

1043
00:58:54.956 --> 00:58:57.116
And when you look at the proline row, there's a bunch of red.

1044
00:58:57.176 --> 00:58:57.486
So that's

1045
00:58:58.416 --> 00:58:59.476
hopefully a good sign.

1046
00:59:00.476 --> 00:59:01.556
Kind of zooming in, we can

1047
00:59:03.336 --> 00:59:06.936
compare to other published functional

1048
00:59:06.976 --> 00:59:10.536
assays. So again, sort of standing on the shoulders of giants here because these

1049
00:59:10.556 --> 00:59:13.685
genes have been deeply studied. There are lots of functional studies,

1050
00:59:15.456 --> 00:59:19.086
sort of more than 100 individual variants that have

1051
00:59:19.096 --> 00:59:22.216
been subjected to individual variant

1052
00:59:22.836 --> 00:59:25.076
functional studies in the past, and we have excellent concordance.

1053
00:59:25.136 --> 00:59:29.056
So here's a known loss of function variant in MLH1, A128

1054
00:59:29.096 --> 00:59:32.996
to P. When we zoom in on that on the heat map, we can see that it has a

1055
00:59:33.036 --> 00:59:36.216
strongly positive score, and this correlates to

1056
00:59:36.876 --> 00:59:40.856
strong loss of function in two previous biochemical assays for MLH1.

1057
00:59:42.576 --> 00:59:46.545
The next thing that we, having kind of satisfied ourselves that, yes, our pooled

1058
00:59:46.596 --> 00:59:49.696
functional screen is well-aligned with

1059
00:59:49.736 --> 00:59:53.096
individual variant assay results that have been previously shown.

1060
00:59:54.136 --> 00:59:57.396
We then need to kind of set out and calibrate this to functional data.

1061
00:59:57.406 --> 01:00:01.336
And so one key thing that we did here in collaboration with colleagues at Ambry

1062
01:00:01.376 --> 01:00:04.936
Genetics was to gather a gold standard set of clinical

1063
01:00:04.996 --> 01:00:08.736
variants, and a kind of a critical criterion was that those

1064
01:00:08.756 --> 01:00:12.456
clinical variants had to stand, their classifications had to

1065
01:00:12.576 --> 01:00:15.596
stand without relying upon functional evidence.

1066
01:00:16.596 --> 01:00:20.196
Because functional assays, whether they're pooled or not pooled, tend to work in

1067
01:00:20.256 --> 01:00:23.346
similar ways, and so one risk is that we could sort of

1068
01:00:24.176 --> 01:00:25.466
have a risk of circularity

1069
01:00:26.276 --> 01:00:29.936
if we are validating our functional assay using somebody else's functional assay.

1070
01:00:30.216 --> 01:00:33.456
So that kind of works on one level that says that, yes, technically these are

1071
01:00:33.476 --> 01:00:34.776
giving us comparable results,

1072
01:00:35.596 --> 01:00:39.496
but maybe clinically we might not be able to

1073
01:00:39.536 --> 01:00:43.216
place as much weight on that type of calibration.

1074
01:00:44.016 --> 01:00:47.516
So we found 48 variants where Ambry's standing

1075
01:00:47.536 --> 01:00:48.016
clinical...

1076
01:00:48.896 --> 01:00:52.336
48 missense variants in MSH2, what I'm showing here.

1077
01:00:52.916 --> 01:00:56.336
Where their standing clinical interpretation didn't depend on functional evidence.

1078
01:00:56.656 --> 01:01:00.556
It was based upon family history, tumor characteristics,

1079
01:01:01.236 --> 01:01:02.596
MMRD status, et cetera.

1080
01:01:03.816 --> 01:01:07.196
And for 47 of those 48 variants, our functional

1081
01:01:07.216 --> 01:01:11.166
data agreed directionally with their standing

1082
01:01:11.216 --> 01:01:15.126
interpretation. And the one that didn't was actually sort of in the region

1083
01:01:15.156 --> 01:01:16.816
that we had defined as being an intermediate.

1084
01:01:16.836 --> 01:01:19.646
So that one we sort of set aside and say, "Well, the MAVE result is somewhere in

1085
01:01:19.656 --> 01:01:21.716
the middle. We don't know what to make of that.

1086
01:01:21.776 --> 01:01:25.716
We're going to exclude it." And so this then meets their various

1087
01:01:25.756 --> 01:01:29.528
kind of acceptedStrength of evidence thresholds, which we've heard

1088
01:01:29.588 --> 01:01:33.128
about, and this meets the threshold for strong evidence.

1089
01:01:33.458 --> 01:01:34.388
And as a result of this,

1090
01:01:35.248 --> 01:01:39.008
in one example study, we and colleagues at Ambry were able to go

1091
01:01:39.048 --> 01:01:42.968
retrospectively into their database of past test

1092
01:01:43.028 --> 01:01:46.998
results and then retrospectively reclassify those,

1093
01:01:47.098 --> 01:01:50.208
and this resulted in the return of 10 new

1094
01:01:50.648 --> 01:01:53.688
diagnoses of Lynch syndrome to 10 individuals.

1095
01:01:55.548 --> 01:01:58.828
We can also look in unselected biobank,

1096
01:01:59.748 --> 01:02:03.248
population-scale biobank data. And so this is one example going in the

1097
01:02:03.608 --> 01:02:06.408
NIH, All of Us cohort,

1098
01:02:07.488 --> 01:02:11.468
where we can look by gene. So I'm showing the four Lynch genes now

1099
01:02:11.508 --> 01:02:14.208
where we've performed these variant-to-function maps.

1100
01:02:14.808 --> 01:02:18.617
And we're looking, we're asking, again, in an association framework,

1101
01:02:19.548 --> 01:02:22.937
if we define all the missense variants that our assays tell us are loss of

1102
01:02:23.008 --> 01:02:26.228
function, how does that associate with risk for

1103
01:02:27.648 --> 01:02:31.628
colorectal cancer? And we get broadly similar results for endometrial cancer.

1104
01:02:32.988 --> 01:02:36.578
And what you can see is this really recapitulates the known pattern where

1105
01:02:36.708 --> 01:02:40.188
MLH1 and MSH2 are very high penetrance,

1106
01:02:40.808 --> 01:02:43.808
and MSH6 and PMS2 are much lower penetrance.

1107
01:02:44.388 --> 01:02:48.338
And we see a very similar pattern, not shown here, for endometrial cancer, with the

1108
01:02:48.388 --> 01:02:51.508
exception that MSH6 kind of comes back up.

1109
01:02:51.688 --> 01:02:54.908
And this matches what's been seen from large-scale

1110
01:02:54.988 --> 01:02:58.928
epidemiology studies of families who are

1111
01:02:58.968 --> 01:03:01.498
carriers for truncating pathogenic variants.

1112
01:03:01.688 --> 01:03:05.648
So now we're doing this for rare missense variants, ones that might

1113
01:03:05.688 --> 01:03:07.528
previously be VUS.

1114
01:03:09.068 --> 01:03:10.288
One thing that we often do and

1115
01:03:11.648 --> 01:03:14.978
has been, I think, a topic of some interest and some

1116
01:03:15.668 --> 01:03:19.428
maybe angst in the field is that we like to compare these results

1117
01:03:19.488 --> 01:03:22.508
to the output of computational predictors.

1118
01:03:22.548 --> 01:03:24.288
And, of course, this is all a lot of work.

1119
01:03:24.988 --> 01:03:28.408
It would be nice if we didn't have to do this work and could just rely on an

1120
01:03:28.488 --> 01:03:31.268
algorithm to give us this map and to resolve VUSs.

1121
01:03:32.308 --> 01:03:36.128
And it is amazing, these algorithms are getting better and better, but one thing

1122
01:03:36.168 --> 01:03:40.088
that we've noticed fairly systematically is that they tend to

1123
01:03:40.168 --> 01:03:42.048
over-call missense pathogenicity.

1124
01:03:42.148 --> 01:03:46.068
So I'm showing you a chunk of our map for PMS2, or actually, this is the

1125
01:03:46.108 --> 01:03:49.998
whole map for PMS2. Where again, blue and white are

1126
01:03:50.608 --> 01:03:53.208
functionally normal, red is functionally abnormal.

1127
01:03:53.748 --> 01:03:57.708
That's the middle panel here. And at the bottom panel, I'm showing what I think

1128
01:03:57.768 --> 01:04:00.968
is widely considered to be one of the best-in-class predictors,

1129
01:04:01.528 --> 01:04:05.308
AlphaMissense. And AlphaMissense provides an output which is a

1130
01:04:05.848 --> 01:04:07.728
so-called probability of pathogenicity.

1131
01:04:07.948 --> 01:04:11.888
And so it provides these scores for every possible missense variant in every gene,

1132
01:04:12.048 --> 01:04:12.908
including PMS2.

1133
01:04:13.828 --> 01:04:16.388
And just right off the bat, you can see there's a lot more red on the bottom.

1134
01:04:17.528 --> 01:04:20.708
So this is not saying that one's right or the other's right, but the

1135
01:04:21.048 --> 01:04:24.298
baseline rates of pathogenicity across genes are very

1136
01:04:25.428 --> 01:04:27.628
starkly different in the case, at least of this gene.

1137
01:04:28.148 --> 01:04:31.588
12% in the case of our MAIV, over 40% in the case of

1138
01:04:31.668 --> 01:04:32.308
AlphaMissense.

1139
01:04:33.448 --> 01:04:37.328
And so to some extent, this can be, we think, addressed by recalibration, so maybe

1140
01:04:37.368 --> 01:04:39.548
setting a different threshold for every gene.

1141
01:04:39.568 --> 01:04:39.658
But

1142
01:04:40.568 --> 01:04:43.328
perhaps it needs to be done at even a finer scale level.

1143
01:04:43.368 --> 01:04:47.288
We might need to go domain by domain, and we can find lots of examples

1144
01:04:47.328 --> 01:04:50.888
where there are variants that clinically seem to be

1145
01:04:51.528 --> 01:04:55.308
benign just on the basis of how many individuals they've been observed in without a

1146
01:04:55.368 --> 01:04:56.268
clear family history.

1147
01:04:57.088 --> 01:05:00.948
And in the cases where we can intersect these, we tend to find

1148
01:05:00.988 --> 01:05:04.808
that the MAIV sort of seems to agree directionally with

1149
01:05:05.068 --> 01:05:06.758
the clinician's interpretation.

1150
01:05:07.528 --> 01:05:11.468
So one thing that we're interested in doing going forward is exploring

1151
01:05:11.508 --> 01:05:15.468
whether we can use MAIV data to fine-tune or improve

1152
01:05:15.708 --> 01:05:16.988
computational predictions.

1153
01:05:18.088 --> 01:05:21.588
One thing that I've gotten really interested in recently is

1154
01:05:21.598 --> 01:05:25.148
stuff in the middle. So we've heard a bit about hypomorphic or

1155
01:05:25.188 --> 01:05:28.688
intermediate variant effects, and these are often--

1156
01:05:30.258 --> 01:05:33.708
In the past, we've sort of just set them aside and said, "Well, the MAIV gives us a

1157
01:05:33.768 --> 01:05:36.168
score in the middle. We don't want to

1158
01:05:37.828 --> 01:05:39.888
be overly aggressive in how we interpret this.

1159
01:05:40.048 --> 01:05:43.988
We're just not going to make a prediction about pathogenicity or benignity

1160
01:05:44.068 --> 01:05:47.247
if we have this." One reason might be that maybe those scores

1161
01:05:47.307 --> 01:05:50.668
are the result of measurement error that's gotten averaged in.

1162
01:05:51.588 --> 01:05:54.108
But there are some interesting case studies, I think, some

1163
01:05:55.448 --> 01:05:58.858
anecdotal examples in the case of some of the, at least the Lynch syndrome genes,

1164
01:05:59.388 --> 01:06:03.028
of variants that really do seem to be hypomorphic and are not

1165
01:06:03.088 --> 01:06:04.628
pathogenic on their own,

1166
01:06:05.508 --> 01:06:05.688
but

1167
01:06:07.728 --> 01:06:11.228
sort of predispose to loss of function that rises to the level of

1168
01:06:11.288 --> 01:06:15.088
pathogenic when there's at least a second genetic

1169
01:06:15.308 --> 01:06:19.288
hit. And so this is an example from MLH1 with a variant called K618A.

1170
01:06:20.108 --> 01:06:24.038
It's relatively common, so we can say with high confidence that it's not

1171
01:06:24.068 --> 01:06:27.238
pathogenic for Lynch on its own. But in

1172
01:06:27.268 --> 01:06:30.768
families where K618A

1173
01:06:30.808 --> 01:06:33.588
co-occurs with a second variant, R659Q,

1174
01:06:34.408 --> 01:06:37.288
Lynch syndrome has been observed in multiple unrelated families.

1175
01:06:38.028 --> 01:06:41.578
And this other one, this other variant, 659Q, is likewise--

1176
01:06:41.938 --> 01:06:44.948
Actually, it's quite rare, but it seems to be functionally normal on its own.

1177
01:06:45.488 --> 01:06:49.128
So is there a potential for an interaction between pairs of

1178
01:06:49.148 --> 01:06:53.128
variants? And of course, this would be relatively rare in the clinic in an

1179
01:06:53.168 --> 01:06:56.888
individual case, sort of squaring things that are rare, but on

1180
01:06:56.988 --> 01:06:57.488
aggregate,

1181
01:06:58.548 --> 01:06:59.268
maybe not so rare.

1182
01:07:00.128 --> 01:07:04.068
So we've set out to do pairwise double mutant screens now, where we make, instead

1183
01:07:04.088 --> 01:07:07.828
of making every possible single missense variant by itself,

1184
01:07:08.428 --> 01:07:12.348
we now-- Well, we do that, or we've already done that, and then we repeat

1185
01:07:12.358 --> 01:07:15.868
that process on the background of something like K618A.

1186
01:07:16.328 --> 01:07:19.248
